Dear Nicky, dear Irene,

As outlined in my first post, it is not true that single-zero studies 
can be included without continuity methods only with Bayesian methods.

The Mantel-Haenszel method is a very simple and also intuitive way to 
include them. If you denote the four entries of a 2x2 table by a,b,c,d, 
the formula (here OR) is

OR.pooled = sum(a*d)/sum(b*c)

If, for example, one of the a's is zero, but not the corresponding c, 
this summand becomes zero in the numerator, but not in the denominator. 
Thus the study is included, and the estimator is well defined, except 
all denominators are zero (no events at all in the second group).

A double-zero is excluded (and does not contribute to the likelihood).

Best,

Gerta

